Buckeye Partners East Chicago Terminal

400 E Columbus Drive, East Chicago, IN 46312
properties.EPA: Buckeye's Chicago hub connects Alberta and North Dakota crude to a pipeline system supplying refineries across the entire Northeast US, as you can see in the map. Look just south of here to see the railcar loader alongside the Hammond terminal.

properties.Name: Buckeye Terminals LLC, 2400 Michigan St., Hammond IN
properties.website: This sprawling tank farm and the one about a mile north constitute the "Chicago Complex." As the corporation explains: "Our Chicago Complex is strategically located at the southern end of Lake Michigan in an area which serves as a busy waypoint for both rail and pipeline traffic. We have identified multiple ways to capitalize on this location and changing crude oil logistics. First, we began operations in late 2013 on a crude oil rail facility that loads crude oil sourced from crude pipelines onto railcars for transportation to East Coast or Gulf Coast refining centers. Second, we are constructing 1.1 million barrels of crude oil storage that will be connected via pipeline to a local refinery to serve as supply redundancy. We also are exploring potential opportunities to utilize existing infrastructure, including rights of way and underutilized pipelines, to be a key logistics service provider in the markets we serve." (from the 2013 annual report)
properties.EPA: Also check out the crude oil loading facility on the southern edge of this facility, just next to the Indiana Harbor Belt Gibson Yard.

properties.Name: Asphalt Operating Services of Chicago
properties.website: The AOS terminal is operational since 2011. Like petcoke, asphalt base is produced from the dregs of heavy oil, and the installation of this new, highly automated terminal on a former Wisconsin Steel site may have been motivated by the need to get rid of huge quantities of that sludge. In the photo, you can see the old KCBX piles in the background.
properties.EPA: Several times I have noticed a large, very new-looking liquids tanker in the collateral channel here, and once I saw the same ship over in Indiana Harbor at the BP dock. While the asphalt leaves by truck and train, it seems to arrive by boat.
